WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm Neil.

5
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Georgie.

6
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.000
In this program, we're discussing a controversial topic that often produces strong feelings.

7
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Should animals be kept in zoos?

8
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
What's your opinion on this debate, Neil?

9
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Oh, it's a really difficult question, Georgie.

10
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I think there are good scientific reasons

11
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:37.000
for having animals in zoos, but also it seems to me a little bit sad and cruel for wild animals to be locked up.

12
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.000
For some, zoos are a good way to teach people about nature and save endangered species from extinction.

13
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Others think separating animals from their natural habitat is cruel and unnecessary.

14
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Either way, with an estimated 700 million visitors every year.

15
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Zoos remain popular, but are they a good thing?

16
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.000
We'll be debating the pros and cons as well as learning some useful new words and phrases.

17
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:09.000
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary for this program on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

18
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Now, I have a question for you, Georgie.

19
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
In 2022, five animals escaped from Sydney's Taronga Zoo in Australia,

20
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:24.000
but were the escaped animals A, elephants, B, lions, or C, zebra's?

21
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
I can imagine zebra's running away from the zoo.

22
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Okay, we'll find out the answer at the end of the program.

23
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Reporter William Lee Adams has been investigating the arguments for and against keeping animal in zoos

24
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
with BBC World Service program, what in the world?

25
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Here, he gives two arguments in favor of zoos.

26
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Education is the primary reason that zoos give for why they should exist.

27
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
The fact is, schoolchildren, all over the world are often busped to zoos.

28
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Remember myself, going to see lowland gorillas at Zoo Atlanta every single year.

29
00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
And the point of this was to introduce us to conservation.

30
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:05.000
One argument for keeping animals in zoos is to educate people about the importance of conservation.

31
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.000
The protection of plants, animals, and the natural world from human damage.

32
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.000
A second point is that zoos often invest in research programs that help endangered animals.

33
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Now, as we know, pandas are notoriously reluctant to mate.

34
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
The female pandas have a narrow window of fertility.

35
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Their solitary creatures, and it takes two to tango when it comes to reproduction.

36
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
But a lot of money in zoos, it goes to sort of find ways to encourage these animals to mate.

37
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
A second argument is that zoos protects endangered species from extinction through breeding.

38
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:46.000
William mentions pandas, animals which are reluctant, meaning slow and unwilling to reproduce.

39
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Male and female pandas need a little help to make babies, and zoos can provide this help.

40
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
William uses the idiom it takes two to tango to describe an activity which needs two people,

41
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
or in this case two pandas, to be willing to make something a success.

42
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Now, let's turn to some of the arguments against zoos with Nikita Darwin, a 19 year old animal rights activist from India,

43
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
who spoke to BBC World Service Program, What In The World.

44
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
I don't think zoos should exist for several reasons.

45
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
The first one being zoos detrimental impact on both the physical and psychological health of animals.

46
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Many studies and research have shown that many animals in zoos and aquariums display abnormal behaviors, like headbalving, pacing, stereotypical behaviors, signs of mental distress.

47
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:39.000
The second reason I would say is that zoos cannot mimic the natural habitat of animals in the wild.

48
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.000
Nikita argues that being enclosed in a zoo is so stressful for wild animals, it leads to abnormal behavior,

49
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
behavior that is different and worse from what would normally be expected.

50
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Examples of this include animals pacing their cages in circles and rocking, bar biting, and even self-harmon.

51
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
And they're so common in captive animals, there's a name for it, zoo-cocess.

52
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Even zoos with large enclosures cannot fully mimic or copy the natural habitats and open spaces these animals would enjoy in the wild.

53
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And imagine how a polar bear evolved for life in the frozen Arctic would feel trapped in a zoo in a much warmer country.

54
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Some zoologists have compared zoo-cocess to human traumas like post-traumatic stress disorder, but say it's even more damaging.

55
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.000
For captive animals, everything, including the air they breathe, is traumatic.

56
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:39.000
We've heard a few arguments for and against keeping animals in zoos. What do you think, Neil? Have you changed your opinion at all?

57
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Well, I think there are really strong arguments on both sides, so I'm still not sure, Georgie.

58
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Well, we know how some of the animals at the Sydney Zoo felt about things because they managed to escape, but what was the answer to your question, Neil?

59
00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Well, Georgie, I asked you which animals escaped from a zoo in Sydney, Australia, in 2022, was it a elephants, b lions or sea zebras?

60
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And I said zebras. I'm afraid. That was the romance, it was actually lions, how scary.

61
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Okay, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learned.

62
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Conservation is the protection of plants, animals, and the natural world from human harm.

63
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
If you are reluctant to do something, you don't want to do it, or you do it very slowly.

64
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:32.000
The idiom it takes two to tango refers to an activity which needs two people to willingly and actively take part for it to succeed.

65
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The adjective abnormal means different from what would normally be expected in a bad way.

66
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Do Kosis is a term to describe the repeated purposeless behavior performed by captive animals in response to the stress of being confined, including pacing, head bobbling and swaying.

67
00:05:50.000 --> 00:06:03.000
And finally, if you mimic somebody or something, you imitate it or copy it. Once again, our six minutes are up, but don't forget we have a worksheet and a quiz that you can use to practice the vocabulary from this episode.

68
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Visit BBCLearningEnglish.com. Goodbye for now.

69
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Goodbye.

70
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
Six minutes English from BBCLearningEnglish.com
